Mission 195: Negi Star Mk2 flight 01

After several decades, the successor to the Negi Star spaceplane is introduced. The Negi Star Mk2 doubles crew capacity from 8 to 16, and is powered by four aerospikes. It also conducts a ballistic re-entry and vertical landing using airbrakes and parachutes instead of gliding to a runway. The ship functions as a second stage, and launch system is now fully reusable for trips to the 500 km parking orbit. (Legs from Kerbal Reusability Expansion)

Mass: 73465 kg

Launch vehicle: K-1b

Y56, D390 (launch)

Spoiler

Stage separation

Docking test with the WiM-14 depot

Re-entry after returning to a 75 km orbit - the skin temperature of the airbrakes reached 90% of the critical temperature

Parachute deployed

Engines were used for the final braking before landing

Mission 198: Negi Maru Append propulsion module 1

Mission 199: Negi Maru Append propulsion module 2

The Negi Maru was augmented with a new engine technology: the CCGC-7 Nuclear Lightbulb (part of Atomic Age, revived as part of SpaceTux Industries Recycled Parts). It is a closed-cycle gas core nuclear engine with a 1500-second specific impulse (compared to 800 seconds). Two propulsion modules provide the Negi Maru with over 15000 m/s of delta-v, allowing the vehicle to visit destinations like Moho, or the more distant outer planets (Urlum, Neidon, and Plock) in a reasonable timeframe.

Mass (each): 112500 kg

Launch vehicle: K-2

Total mass of Negi Maru Append: 411329 kg
